PROGRAM TO EXPLORE STRING AND STRINGBUFFER METHODS
12 Feb 2026


AIM:
To demonstrate the use of String and StringBuffer methods in Java using command-line arguments. 


ALGORITHM;
Step 1: Start the program.
Step 2: Create a String variable and assign a value.
Step 3: Apply String methods:
Find length
Convert to uppercase and lowercase
Extract substring
Compare strings
Find index of character
Step 4: Display all String results.
Step 5: Create a StringBuffer object.
Step 6: Apply StringBuffer methods:
Append text
Insert text
Replace text
Delete text
Reverse string
Step 7: Display all StringBuffer results.
Step 8: Stop the program.
















SOURCE CODE :
package textops;
pub package textops;
public class StringBufferOperations {
private String str;
public StringBufferOperations(String str) {
this.str = str;
}
public void exploreStringBufferMethods(String appendStr) {
System.out.println("\n----- StringBuffer Methods -----");
StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer(str);
System.out.println("Original StringBuffer: " + sb);
sb.append(appendStr);
System.out.println("After append: " + sb);
sb.insert(0, "Start-");
System.out.println("After insert: " + sb);
sb.replace(0, 5, "Begin");
System.out.println("After replace: " + sb);
sb.delete(0, 6);
System.out.println("After delete: " + sb);
sb.reverse();
System.out.println("After reverse: " + sb);
System.out.println("Capacity: " + sb.capacity());
System.out.println("Length: " + sb.length());
}
